00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:15.889
Valeriano Fatica carves fruits and vegetables
on his youtube channel, “Ortolano Production”.

00:00:15.889 --> 00:00:21.200
Using a variety of knives and scrapers he
turns watermelons into unicorns, pumpkins

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:26.430
into the joker, and even uploads tutorials
for budding fruit carvers like how to turn

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:28.180
a lemon into a mouse.

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:34.070
Matthias Wandel is a prolific builder with
a remarkable YouTube channel focused on woodworking.

00:00:34.070 --> 00:00:39.360
His videos tend to pair up with a more detailed
explanation on his website so you’ll be

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:46.269
building tiny boxes, a wasp sucking machine,
or even a wooden combination lock in no time.

00:00:46.269 --> 00:00:49.160
This guy is the definition of build it.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.719
teamLab built an interactive flower garden
that smells different depending on what time

00:00:53.719 --> 00:00:56.690
of day it is and also moves as you move.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:01:02.449
The Floating Garden has over 2,300 living
flowers that rise up in a circle around the

00:01:02.449 --> 00:01:05.689
viewer, making them feel like they're at the
center of the garden at all times.

00:01:05.689 --> 00:01:10.710
And it was built to evoke certain zen teachings
of interconnectedness.

00:01:10.710 --> 00:01:11.710
Draw it.

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:17.170
Malaysian artist Hong Yi created a giant portrait
using 20,000 bags of tea.

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:22.200
It took two months to finish and depicts a
man preparing a famous type of tea called

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:24.560
teh tarik, which means pulled tea.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:29.060
Hong Yi says she created the piece because
she wanted to recreate an everyday scene unique

00:01:29.060 --> 00:01:30.859
to the culture of Malaysia.

00:01:30.859 --> 00:01:35.859
Amy Shackleton is a painter who uses condiment
bottles instead of brushes.

00:01:35.859 --> 00:01:41.200
By using a rotating canvas, water, and squeeze
bottles she paints colorful works that bring

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:46.380
together the rigid straight lines of a city
with the organic movements of nature.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:52.289
And she hopes her paintings inspire conversations
about the cohabitation of humans and the environment.

00:01:52.289 --> 00:02:09.140
And now for the work of Julia Dillon, a freelance
sci fi and fantasy artist from California.

00:02:09.140 --> 00:02:13.130
Lorraine Loots has an ongoing series called
paintings for ants.

00:02:13.130 --> 00:02:18.120
She plans to paint 100 miniature pictures
this year and picks her subject based on what

00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:22.159
day of the week it is, like Microcosm Mondays,
or Free Fridays.

00:02:22.159 --> 00:02:27.099
She’s auctioning off each painting on instagram
so if you know any ants that love art, let

00:02:27.099 --> 00:02:28.330
them know.

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:29.480
